data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, EF Core's Cosmos DB provider allowed you to opt back into **sync-over-async** execution (e.g., via `CosmosOptionsExtension` or the `EnableSyncExecution` flag). **In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, etc.) now throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally against the Cosmos DB provider.

## The fix

Convert every synchronous call to its `async` counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`, renamed with `Async` suffix
- `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`

You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through every caller in the chain (controllers, services, etc.). Remove any `EnableSyncExecution` configuration — it's no longer recognized.
